props.synopsis: Emails obtained by the ABC under a Right to Information request reveal police had detailed information about Nathaniel Train almost a year before the Wieambilla attack.

title.children: Emails show police had detailed information about Nathaniel Train a year before Wieambilla terror attack

image.altText: Floodwaters have inundated Wujal Wujal.

props.synopsis: "Significant additional support" will be rolled out for those affected by flooding in Far North Queensland, as Prime Minister Anthony Albanese meets with emergency service workers and volunteers today.

title.children: Further recovery support announced for Far North Queensland as Kowanyama braces for floods

image.altText: Chopper pilot rescued multiple people from flooded areas

props.synopsis: The pilot, who leapt into action to fly a group of people stranded on the roof of the Lion's Den Pub to safety one-by-one, is being lauded as the "real hero" of the flood rescue efforts.

title.children: Meet 'Magoo', the chopper pilot who saved 16 people from a pub roof in Far North Queensland

image.altText: A bunch of people stand on a dry section of road that is completely flooded ahead of them.

props.synopsis: An ABC analysis of events which unfolded last week shows the bureau's rain forecasts after Jasper's landfall were hindered by very poor modelling of the system's track.

title.children: Did the Bureau of Meteorology drop the ball in its Tropical Cyclone Jasper forecasts?

image.altText: Sillohuetes of 61 women imposed over the house of representatives.

props.synopsis: The ABC contacted every male MP in the House of Representatives to ask what is being done in their electorates about a family violence crisis that has seen more than 50 women killed this year.

title.children: The ABC contacted every federal male MP about domestic violence deaths. Here's what they said

image.altText: Carl Webb playing for Queensland in 2008.

props.synopsis: Former Queensland and Australian representative Carl Webb passes away following a four-year battle with motor neurone disease.

title.children: Former State of Origin player Carl Webb dies aged 42

image.altText: A Bonza aircraft on a runway.

props.synopsis: Outback Queensland residents are in uproar as another round of flight cancellations means families will be separated for Christmas, or forced to pay thousands of dollars for last-minute flights.

title.children: Sudden Bonza flight cancellations leave outback residents stranded for Christmas

image.altText: A sign on an exterior wall says St Vincent's Hospital Melbourne

props.synopsis: St Vincent's Health says there is evidence that "some data" has been removed from its system, but it is still working to determine what information had been stolen.

title.children: Data stolen in cyber attack on St Vincent's Health network

image.altText: A shopper wearing a mask walks past a Christmas display outside a David Jones department store

props.synopsis: JN.1 appears to be more transmissible than some previous variants and, with so many of us travelling and gathering with others right now, the conditions are right for the virus to spread.

title.children: Some states say COVID cases are up before Christmas. Here's what may be behind the rise

image.altText: Eleanor Ahern is 11 months old and has lived in a medical bubble for most of her life

props.synopsis: Elle was born with a severe immune system disorder that makes her highly susceptible to infections, but doctors believe she'll eventually be able to live a normal life.

title.children: Elle's immune system is so severely compromised she has to live in a bubble with her 'bubble mummy'

image.altText: A girl in a wheelchair smiles while her mum stands next to her

props.synopsis: The volunteers from the Woodturners Society of Queensland work all year to handcraft wooden toys to give to children in need during the festive season.

title.children: Volunteer woodworkers labour like Santa's elves to make toys for kids in need

image.altText: Side profile headshot of a mother hugging her daughter, looking glum

props.synopsis: Authorities in Western Australia remain on high alert after five bushfire emergencies in two days destroyed homes and caused major disruption.

title.children: 'There aren't any words': Family in shock as bushfire destroys home days out from Christmas

image.altText: Artist impression of waterpark with big lake in the middle

props.synopsis: A company owned by the developer behind a long-awaited water park and surf pool project on Queensland's Sunshine Coast has gone into administration, with the land to be put on the market early in the new year.

title.children: $350m Sunshine Coast water park plan in jeopardy as developer's company folds

image.altText: A man with a moustache in front of a party tent.

props.synopsis: Suspended Gold Coast councillor Ryan Bayldon-Lumsden, who is accused of killing his stepfather earlier this year, says he will run in the 2024 local government elections.

title.children: Ryan Bayldon-Lumsden says he's running for council while on bail after being charged with murder

image.altText: Two men stand and smile on the deck of a yacht.

props.synopsis: Skipper Peter Webster has sailed the Sydney to Hobart three times before but this year he has dreamt up an idea to challenge teams with multimillion-dollar campaigns behind them.

title.children: Unlike their multimillion-dollar competitors, this crew is tackling the Sydney to Hobart on a shoestring budget

image.altText: A composite image of Paul Rath, Richard Slater, Carl Stockton men who died in suspected gay hate crimes

props.synopsis: Young men found dead at the bottom of cliffs and a grandfather fatally beaten in a public toilet are among the deaths that should be subject to fresh inquests, a NSW Special Commission of Inquiry has found.

title.children: The 'lonely, terrifying' deaths of these men reveal Sydney's dark past

image.altText: People hide on the roof of a building.

props.synopsis: A lone gunman opens fire at Prague's Charles University, killing at least 14 people and injuring 20 others in Czechia's worst mass shooting.

title.children: Czechia president says Prague university mass shooting 'most tragic day' in country's history

image.altText: A shot of a wind turbine from below.

props.synopsis: The project involves the construction of 208 wind turbines, each with a maximum height of 270 metres, on the outskirts of Jerilderie in New South Wales' Riverina region.

title.children: One of NSW's largest wind farms given the green light for construction

image.altText: Ryan holds a bottle of passionfruit liqueur and some passionfruit while standing among passionfruit vines.

props.synopsis: A patch of gravel in Wollongong's CBD is turned into a thriving farm and distillery, producing products designed to compete with international alcohol giants on price and quality while reducing waste.

title.children: Tiny urban farm built on old carpark making boutique booze to rival big liquor brands

image.altText: a mine site with a big truck and white rock

props.synopsis: Shares in Core Lithium have crashed by more than 20 per cent this morning after the company announced it was reviewing its operations near Darwin because of "the deterioration in lithium market conditions".

title.children: Lithium mine near Darwin considers halt as market 'deteriorates'

image.altText: A man's face in front of a generic hospital background with an added heart beat symbol

props.synopsis: Dr Nathan William Dawe strangled his victim and hit her with a wedding photo album in Canberra last year. He avoided jail and received an 18-month good behaviour bond in the ACT Magistrates Court. The national health practitioner regulator says it's monitoring his case.

title.children: Doctor avoids jail after choking, threatening to send victim to mental health unit in 'cowardly' domestic violence attack

image.altText: A portrait of a blonde-haired woman wearing a pink button-up shirt.

props.synopsis: When a landlord association headed by an Airbnb owner and mayoral aspirant was given a grant, it raised questions. An audit has found multiple concerns.

title.children: A landlord body was given a $100,000 government grant. The way it was spent raised questions

image.altText: Black and white photograph of a boat docked in Yokohoma.

props.synopsis: In 1926, hundreds of US students set off on one of the world's first study abroad adventures, docking in nearly 50 ports around the world. But it wasn't without its critics.

title.children: In 1926, hundreds of students boarded a ship for a controversial experiment. It changed their lives

image.altText: A man jumps into the the lower house of the Indian Parliament.

props.synopsis: More than half of India's opposition MPs are barred from the ongoing session of India's parliament for demanding a debate over a protest last week. Now it has prompted questions over the Narendra Modi government's handling of dissent.

title.children: When two men walked into India's parliament, it was standard procedure. What followed was anything but

image.altText: A car crashed through the wall of a pub.

props.synopsis: Random breath testing has been a familiar part of Australia's road safety landscape for decades, but when it was introduced it was seen as a radical move.

title.children: Australia's road toll peaked in the 1960s and 70s. Then something radical was proposed

image.altText: a woman with blonde hair, black jumper stands next to man with blue shirt, next to a woman in pink shirt on motorised scooter

props.synopsis: A mining company has been accused of misleading the community to garner support for a mine proposal being assessed by the Victorian government.

title.children: 'I did not write that submission': Locals angry mining company misrepresented them to win government support

image.altText: A middle-aged woman smiles at the camera.

props.synopsis: Helen Bird died in 2010. Her death is being re-examined at a coronial inquest, which has heard her husband, who has been named a person of interest, has given differing accounts of Helen's state before her death.

title.children: Husband ran to landline rather than use his mobile and perform CPR when he found wife's body, inquest hears

image.altText: A turtle swimming over the coral reef in blue waters.

props.synopsis: With Far North Queensland's peak tourism period disrupted by a cyclone and flooding, the state government wants Australians to show their support by continuing with plans to visit the region for a holiday.

title.children: Do you have a holiday booked in Far North Queensland this Christmas? Don't cancel it yet

image.altText: The side of a building damaged with bricks on the ground

props.synopsis: A year on from South Australia's River Murray floods, a "long list" of infrastructure repairs remain unfinished, popular tourist destinations are still in ruin and some residents are having to go it alone.

title.children: ‘It is absolutely disgusting’: It's been one year since flooding hit this region and residents are still cleaning up

image.altText: A woman smiles looking straight at the camera. She's wearing a red Christmas T-shirt and sunglasses.

props.synopsis: Paradee Titulaer didn't know what Christmas was until she moved to Australia aged 11. She now runs a year-round Christmas shop.

title.children: Christmas shop workers say business is up, and there's a surprising Christmas character catching up to Santa
